## Baseline

Before diving into any ML project it is essential to be acquainted with the data. In terms of text data and tabular data, we have to perform extensive EDA to get a holistic understanding of the data. IN case of images it becomes slightly easier to understand the data and when you have a smaller dataset i.e **number of examples = 18 * 50 = 900** then even a manual scan can is sufficient. Before commenting on the data, lets take the raw dataset and create a baseline model on the dataset. A baseline **helps you understand your task** . **Beyond learning from your data**, a baseline model will allow you to see which parts of your inference are easy, and which parts are hard [[Ref]](https://blog.insightdatascience.com/always-start-with-a-stupid-model-no-exceptions-3a22314b9aaa#:~:text=A%20baseline%20helps%20you%20understand%20your%20task,and%20which%20parts%20are%20hard.). `It is sort of a like **Trial and error** that mad scientists do in their laboratories but meant for Data Scientists.`

Most machine learning models are against the 'one size fits them all' theorem and we have try our different possibilites to reach to an optimal solution - its like finding the right paramters by performing gradient descent, we start of with some randomly initialized weights, make some mistakes and update our parameters to get to an optimal result.

 #### Transfer Learning

Transfer learning has revolutionized computer vision and its sister fields of deep learning. In practice, very few people train an entire Convolutional Network from scratch (with random initialization), because it is relatively rare to have a dataset of sufficient size. Instead, it is common to pretrain a ConvNet on a very large dataset (e.g. ImageNet, which contains 1.2 million images with 1000 categories), and then use the ConvNet either as an initialization or a fixed feature extractor for the task of interest.

![](https://www.topbots.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/cover_transfer_learning_1600px_web.jpg)

Hence in this assessments instead of using a Densely connected network or Simple Convolutional Layers followed by a Fully connected network I have opted for using the state-of-the-art models in research that have delivered optimal results. In this assessment I have tried out three models - the Resnet34 model, the Resnet 101 model and the current state-of-the-art -> the efficientnet architecture. [[Ref]](https://cs231n.github.io/transfer-learning/)

Since we are dealing with limited data samples, we are going to need to augment the data, i.e generate new images with some particularly defined transforms. 

```python
item_tfms = RandomResizedCrop(460, min_scale=0.75, ratio=(1.,1.))
batch_tfms = [*aug_transforms(size=224, max_warp=0), Normalize.from_stats(*imagenet_stats)]
bs=8
```

Item transforms are applicable to a single image from the dataset while batch transforms are applied homogenously over the entire batch of the dataloader. 

For item transformers we will use RandomResizedCrop which picks a random scaled crop of an image and resize it to `size`

The crop picked as a random scale in range `(min_scale,max_scale)` and `ratio` in the range passed, then the resize is done with `resamples[0]` for images and `resamples[1]` for segmentation masks. On the validation set, we center crop the image if it's ratio isn't in the range (to the minmum or maximum value) then resize.

For the batch transformations we will resize each image from our batch to a size 224X224 which is the input size of most transfer learning mmodels in the literature today. We warp the perspective by specifying the max_warp parameter and normalize the images since we intend to use a pretrained model for our task, so we need to normalize our data by the original model's data's statistics.

Here we load the data from our training dataframe using the ImageDataLoaders class which is the highest level of API for loading data. We pass all the required parameters into the dataloader.

#### Resnets 

The ResNet architecture was the winner of 2015 ILSVRC and was proposed by He et al. The main novelty behind the success of ResNets were the use of residual layers and skip connections which solved the vanishing gradients problem that may result in stopping the weights in the network to further change. Skipping connections will help gradients to flow backwards directly from end layers to initial layer filters enabling CNN models to deepen with a number of layers. They stack residual blocks on top of each other to form a complete network e.g. Resnet101 has 101 layers using these blocks. In our study we have implemented fine tuning on Resnet 34 and Resnet 101.



```python
learn = cnn_learner(dls, resnet34, pretrained=True, metrics=[accuracy]).to_fp16()
learn.fit_one_cycle(1)
learn.lr_find()
```

Since our dataset has relatively few samples in each classes, we might have to perform **Data Augmentation** on it.  

Data augmentation is the process of getting more data by making minor alterations to our existing dataset. Minor changes such as flips or translations or rotations. Our neural network would think these are distinct images anyway. . In the real world scenario, we may have a dataset of images taken in a limited set of conditions. But, our target application may exist in a variety of conditions, such as different orientation, location, scale, brightness etc. We account for these situations by training our neural network with additional synthetically modified data. We use the transforms module provided by Pytorch with a set of functions for resizing, flipping and cropping the images. The best part about Data Augmentation is that **the images are not stored in ram** and are used on the go hence very efficient for deep learning.

```python

data_transforms = {
    'train': transforms.Compose([
        transforms.RandomResizedCrop(224),
        transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406], [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    ]),
    'val': transforms.Compose([
        transforms.Resize(256),
        transforms.CenterCrop(224),
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406], [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    ]),
}
```

```python
def show_batch(image, title):
  image = image.numpy().transpose((1, 2, 0))
  mean = np.array([0.485, 0.456, 0.406])
  std = np.array([0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
  image = std * image + mean
  plt.imshow(image)
  if title:
    plt.title(title)
  plt.pause(0.001)

inputs, classes = next(iter(train_loader))
out = torchvision.utils.make_grid(inputs)

show_batch(out, title = [class_names[x] for x in classes])
```

We will now use the efficientnet model which is the current state of the art in image classification. 

With the rise of transfer learning, the essentiality of scaling has been deeply realised for enhancing the performance as well as efficieny of models. Traditionaly scaling can be done in three dimensions viz. depth, width and resolution in terms of convolutional neural networks. Depth scaling pertains to increasing the number of layers in the model, making it more deeper; width scaling makes the model wider (one possible way is to increase the number of channels in a layer) and resolution scaling means using high resolution images so that features are more fine-grained. Each method applied individually has some drawbacks such as in depth scaling we have the problem of vanishing gradients and in width scaling the accuracy saturates after a point and there is a limit to increasing resolution of images and a slight increase doesnt result in significant improvement of performance. Hence Efficientnets are proposed to deal with balancing all dimensions of a network during CNN scaling for getting improved accuracy and efficieny. The authors proposed a simple yet very effective scaling technique which uses a compound coefficientto uniformly scale network width, depth, and resolution in a principled way. We used the pytorch wrapper for efficientnets. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)



```python
from efficientnet_pytorch import EfficientNet
model = EfficientNet.from_pretrained('efficientnet-b3')
```

If we print the model we shall be getting a number of layers stacked on top of each other. There consist mainly of Convolutional Layers followed by BatchNormalization and a new block called MBConv introduced by the researchers of the efficientnet paper.

In order to fine tune the model on our dataset all we have to do is add a fully connected layer of our own and append it to the end of the model. We do this by taking the input shape of the last layer and changing it to the output dimensions that we desire, in our case it is 18 - corresponding to the number of unique classes of logos.

> **We then define a loss function for our model which will measure the distance between the predictions and the actual ground truth labels.** 

> **Additionally we need an Optimization function which will calculate and update gradients of the parameters for the model. We use the Stochastic Gradient Descent Optimizer which calculates the loss function per single sample which makes it the fastest optimizer available. Other options available are the Mini-Batch Gradient Descent and the Adam optimizer.** 

> **Additionally we define an Lr scheduler which will modify the changing of the learning rate as we go ahead with our training. It makes sure that we take large steps when we are far from the global minimum and take smaller steps as we reach the minimum.** 

```python

num_ftrs = model._fc.in_features
model.fc = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, len(class_names))
model= model.to(device)
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.001, momentum = 0.9)

exp_lr_scheduler = lr_scheduler.StepLR(optimizer, step_size=7, gamma=0.1)
```

Now we come to the crux of the problem - In the above codeblock we have defined the forward propagation for the data in our train function what we shall be doing is the main ingredient of training neural networks - gradient descent. 

For some particular number of epochs we do the following -

1. Define variables for storing the running loss.
2. For each image bunch and label bunch in the respective dataloaders, we will
3. Pass the images through the forward propagation algorithm defined by our model. The model will estimate probabilities and the output shape of the predictions will match the dimensions of our output vector.
4. Nextup we calculate the loss function i.e how far away the models predictions are from the ground truth, this is an important metric which is used to send back the signals in backpropagation to update gradients in the negative direction to help them reach the global minimum.
5. Before taking the gradient step, we clear out the gradients accumulated by our optimizer and calculate gradients using loss.backward. 
6. We then update the model weights by optimizer.step() function and add the loss calculated to the running loss.
7. At the end of all epochs we calculate the total loss by dividing the running loss by the number of samples we have encountered.

```python
# train for some number of epochs
epochs = 30
print_every = 1
for epoch in range(1, epochs + 1):
    train_loss = 0.0
    total_train = 0
    model.train()
    print(f'Training Model...')
    for image, labels in tqdm(train_loader):
        image = image.to(device)
        labels = labels.to(device)
        outputs = model(image)
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        train_loss += loss.item() * labels.shape[0]
        total_train += labels.shape[0]
    if epoch % 2 == 0:
        model.eval()
        val_loss = 0.0
        total_val = 0
        correct = 0
        print(f'Evaluating Model...')
        for image, labels in tqdm(test_loader):
            image = image.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            outputs = model(image)
            _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            correct += (preds == labels).sum()
            total_val += labels.shape[0]
            val_loss = loss.item() * labels.shape[0]
        print('Validation Loss : {:.8f} || Accuracy : {:.3f}'.format((val_loss / total_val) , (correct / total_val) * 100))
        
    if epoch % print_every == 0:
        print(epoch)
        print('Train Loss : {:.3f}'.format((train_loss /total_train)))
```

For evaluation we put the model in eval mode and calculate how many correct examples have been encountered by the model.

```python
test_losses = []
model.eval()
num_correct = 0
for image, labels in tqdm(test_loader):
    image = image.to(device)
    labels = labels.to(device)
    outputs = model(image)
    _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)
    num_correct += torch.sum(preds == labels)
    loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
    test_losses.append(loss.item())
print("Test loss: {:.3f}".format(np.mean(test_losses)))
test_acc = num_correct/len(test_loader.dataset)
print("Test accuracy: {:.3f} %".format(test_acc * 100))
```

```python
def visualize_model(model, num_images=12):
    was_training = model.training
    model.eval()
    images_so_far = 0
    fig = plt.figure()

    with torch.no_grad():
        for i, (inputs, labels) in enumerate(test_loader):
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)

            outputs = model(inputs)
            _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)

            for j in range(inputs.size()[0]):
                images_so_far += 1
                ax = plt.subplot(num_images//2, 2, images_so_far)
                ax.axis('off')
                ax.set_title('predicted: {}'.format(class_names[preds[j]]))
                show_batch(inputs.cpu().data[j], title = None)

                if images_so_far == num_images:
                    model.train(mode=was_training)
                    return
        model.train(mode=was_training)
```

## Problems Encountered and how can the model be made better.

### 1. Logos of car companies arent homogenous in all cases :

For example take the example of Cheverolet - it has a completely different logo for the Corvettes and a completely different logo for other cars.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

This means that the data points are not homogenous and not centered around the mean, there is a vast deviation in the data across all three channels RGB hence it makes it difficult for the model to comprehend these cases.

IN order to counter this problem I manually cleaned the data by looking at the images that werent helping much in classification or where the logo was not clearly visible. 

#### 2 .The transfer learning model instead of being fine tuned, could be used simply as a feature extractor.

By setting the gradients of the parameters to requires_grad = False, we are freezing the model weights and are only using it as a feature extractor. This cuts down the cost to train the model entirely as we only end up training the fully connected layer attached to the model and the model is only used to extract valuable features from the dataset. 

#### 3. More data is always great!

In case of deep neural networks, they perform really well when there is large amount of data available. For our use case each sample, although properly balanced, had only 50 images in each classes which is less compared to models trained on the imagenet dataset where there are 1000 classes and 1000 examples in each cases making it a comprehensive dataset. We used data augmentation to produce more samples which replicate the images from the dataset but tjhey are not enough, we can always search the web for more amount of data to train our models.
